00:00:52.130 --> 00:00:54.280
in Uganda, and just
recently switched back

00:00:54.280 --> 00:00:55.900
over to the finance
side in New York.

00:00:58.720 --> 00:01:01.390
And what GiveDirectly does
is pretty straight forward.

00:01:01.390 --> 00:01:05.530
We send cash unconditionally
to people living mostly

00:01:05.530 --> 00:01:07.270
in extreme poverty.

00:01:07.270 --> 00:01:08.660
That cash is a grant.

00:01:08.660 --> 00:01:09.730
It's not a loan.

00:01:09.730 --> 00:01:12.060
People can spend it
however they want.

00:01:12.060 --> 00:01:16.150
In the most typical model,
we will send about $1,000

00:01:16.150 --> 00:01:18.460
in a couple of chunks over
the course of a few months.

00:01:18.460 --> 00:01:21.820
And then people spend it
on whatever they want.

00:01:21.820 --> 00:01:24.460
In total, we've raised
almost $150 million

00:01:24.460 --> 00:01:26.290
to deliver as cash transfers.

00:01:26.290 --> 00:01:29.230
And we've enrolled
over 80,000 households.

00:01:29.230 --> 00:01:31.840
Because our operations are
fairly straightforward,

00:01:31.840 --> 00:01:33.460
we're able to stay
remarkably lean.

00:01:33.460 --> 00:01:35.740
And so, on average,
about 90% of what

00:01:35.740 --> 00:01:38.620
we raise for cash transfers
gets delivered directly

00:01:38.620 --> 00:01:41.260
to people's hands at
the end of the day.

00:01:41.260 --> 00:01:43.150
And then as we're
doing all of this work,

00:01:43.150 --> 00:01:44.816
we're constantly
running different types

00:01:44.816 --> 00:01:45.850
of research studies.

00:01:45.850 --> 00:01:47.620
And so when we first
got started in Kenya,

00:01:47.620 --> 00:01:49.240
we ran a randomized
controlled trial

00:01:49.240 --> 00:01:52.390
testing a bunch of different
things about cash transfers--

00:01:52.390 --> 00:01:58.090
comparing large lump sum cash
transfers to recurring stream

00:01:58.090 --> 00:02:02.050
transfers, testing whether or
not male recipients spend money

00:02:02.050 --> 00:02:04.506
differently from
female recipients,

00:02:04.506 --> 00:02:06.130
as well as the effect
of cash transfers

00:02:06.130 --> 00:02:08.740
on a ton of different
outcome variables, earnings

00:02:08.740 --> 00:02:10.780
and assets, consumption,
but also things

00:02:10.780 --> 00:02:13.177
like stress and depression
and things like that.

00:02:13.177 --> 00:02:15.760
Since then, we've done a number
of different research studies.

00:02:15.760 --> 00:02:18.670
We can talk about things like
looking at the effects of cash

00:02:18.670 --> 00:02:20.730
transfers on macro--

00:02:20.730 --> 00:02:23.140
the macro aspects
of the economy--

00:02:23.140 --> 00:02:27.130
behavioral aspects
of cash transfers,

00:02:27.130 --> 00:02:29.530
how cash transfers
affect coffee farmers,

00:02:29.530 --> 00:02:33.310
and how they invest in their
farms and things like that.

00:02:33.310 --> 00:02:37.330
Operationally, the process looks
a lot like a sales and customer

00:02:37.330 --> 00:02:38.630
service operations.

00:02:38.630 --> 00:02:40.750
We'll go door to
door and collect data

00:02:40.750 --> 00:02:42.640
on the people who
could potentially

00:02:42.640 --> 00:02:46.420
receive cash transfers,
run a pretty simple logic

00:02:46.420 --> 00:02:48.934
to decide who is
eligible, then go back

00:02:48.934 --> 00:02:50.350
and collect a
little bit more data

00:02:50.350 --> 00:02:53.430
and inform them
about the program.

00:02:53.430 --> 00:02:56.140
We'll then send the money,
typically through Mobile Money.

00:02:56.140 --> 00:02:58.330
And so that looks
like Venmo, but you're

00:02:58.330 --> 00:03:01.480
able to cash out basically
anywhere around you.

00:03:01.480 --> 00:03:03.730
And we can send
thousands of payments

00:03:03.730 --> 00:03:06.536
with a touch on a laptop.

00:03:06.536 --> 00:03:08.160
And then we have full
time call centers

00:03:08.160 --> 00:03:09.980
in each of the
countries where we work.

00:03:09.980 --> 00:03:11.860
And so after every
time we send payments,

00:03:11.860 --> 00:03:14.068
we're able to call people
up and confirm that they've

00:03:14.068 --> 00:03:16.660
received it, ask if they have
any feedback for GiveDirectly,

00:03:16.660 --> 00:03:18.451
and understand if
they've had any problems.

00:03:20.790 --> 00:03:24.290
Now that model of just
giving unconditional cash

00:03:24.290 --> 00:03:27.710
is very different from how
we're taught through aphorisms

00:03:27.710 --> 00:03:30.680
or parables about how we're
supposed to approach giving.

00:03:30.680 --> 00:03:33.230
There's this idea that you're
supposed to teach a man to fish

00:03:33.230 --> 00:03:34.640
or not give him a fish.

00:03:34.640 --> 00:03:38.610
Or that you should give a
hand up but not a handout.

00:03:38.610 --> 00:03:41.210
And I think behind that, there's
this idea that giving cash

00:03:41.210 --> 00:03:42.620
can't be sustainable.

00:03:42.620 --> 00:03:45.350
And there's also this idea
that we should distrust

00:03:45.350 --> 00:03:49.370
the people we're trying to help
somehow, that giving them money

00:03:49.370 --> 00:03:50.630
could be corrupting.

00:03:50.630 --> 00:03:52.340
Or if it's not
corrupting, that we just

00:03:52.340 --> 00:03:56.060
can't trust from the outset
that it could be spent well.

00:03:56.060 --> 00:03:58.190
Behind that basic
debate, the stakes

00:03:58.190 --> 00:04:00.800
are actually remarkably
high between how we

00:04:00.800 --> 00:04:02.810
should approach helping people.

00:04:02.810 --> 00:04:04.730
To give you a sense,
this is one way

00:04:04.730 --> 00:04:09.420
of visualizing
what's up for debate.

00:04:09.420 --> 00:04:12.360
The blue line is global
official development assistance.

00:04:12.360 --> 00:04:14.120
It's one measure of
this total amount

00:04:14.120 --> 00:04:17.000
that governments are
spending in foreign aid.

00:04:17.000 --> 00:04:19.100
The line that's
going down over time

00:04:19.100 --> 00:04:21.740
is the cost of closing
the poverty gap.

00:04:21.740 --> 00:04:23.690
You can think of this
as taking everyone

00:04:23.690 --> 00:04:25.820
who is below the
global poverty line

00:04:25.820 --> 00:04:28.790
and visualizing how much in
cash it would take to get them

00:04:28.790 --> 00:04:30.145
to the poverty line.

00:04:30.145 --> 00:04:31.520
Now, there's a
lot of reasons why

00:04:31.520 --> 00:04:34.670
that's a simplistic
picture of what's going on.

00:04:34.670 --> 00:04:38.810
But the basic synthesis is that
we have incredible resources

00:04:38.810 --> 00:04:41.440
available to help the
people we're trying to help,

00:04:41.440 --> 00:04:43.760
to help the people
in extreme poverty.

00:04:43.760 --> 00:04:47.120
And a lot of the problem
of aid and development

00:04:47.120 --> 00:04:48.860
is an allocation
one-- that it's not

00:04:48.860 --> 00:04:50.390
so much that we
need more resources,

00:04:50.390 --> 00:04:52.260
but we need to
better allocate them.

00:04:52.260 --> 00:04:54.350
And so this debate
about how best should we

00:04:54.350 --> 00:04:59.430
help people is actually
extremely important.

00:04:59.430 --> 00:05:01.000
So luckily, we
don't have to have

00:05:01.000 --> 00:05:06.070
this debate in this arena
of dueling assertions.

00:05:06.070 --> 00:05:08.590
It doesn't have to be this
theoretical or philosophical

00:05:08.590 --> 00:05:10.900
debate about what
people are really like.

00:05:10.900 --> 00:05:12.420
We can test it.

00:05:12.420 --> 00:05:14.950
A development that's happened
over this last couple

00:05:14.950 --> 00:05:17.680
of decades within
development economics

00:05:17.680 --> 00:05:19.720
is moving a little
bit away from theory

00:05:19.720 --> 00:05:24.820
towards actually putting things
into experimental evaluations.

00:05:24.820 --> 00:05:26.620
And so the gold standard
approach to this

00:05:26.620 --> 00:05:29.010
is what's called a
randomized control trial.

00:05:29.010 --> 00:05:30.760
It's the same way that
we test medicines--

00:05:30.760 --> 00:05:33.820
by randomly assigning people
to either receive or not

00:05:33.820 --> 00:05:36.735
receive a treatment and then
using external evaluators

00:05:36.735 --> 00:05:40.510
to test the differences in the
different outcome variables

00:05:40.510 --> 00:05:42.126
between those two groups.

00:05:42.126 --> 00:05:43.750
We've learned a lot
of different things

00:05:43.750 --> 00:05:46.545
from that about different
interventions we use.

00:05:46.545 --> 00:05:47.920
We've learned that
we're actually

00:05:47.920 --> 00:05:51.610
pretty bad at training people
or teaching people to fish.

00:05:51.610 --> 00:05:53.830
The effects of
microfinance and things

00:05:53.830 --> 00:05:55.660
like that are
actually pretty mixed.

00:05:55.660 --> 00:05:57.910
We've also learned that
the effects of cash

00:05:57.910 --> 00:06:02.770
are remarkably consistent,
that the exact impacts can vary

00:06:02.770 --> 00:06:05.680
a lot by the structure
of the cash transfers

00:06:05.680 --> 00:06:08.650
or the people who are
receiving them or the context.

00:06:08.650 --> 00:06:11.120
But you see a few
consistent themes.

00:06:11.120 --> 00:06:13.240
First, people spend
it pretty well.

00:06:13.240 --> 00:06:16.180
You see increases in
earnings and consumption,

00:06:16.180 --> 00:06:19.600
decreases in food insecurity,
improvements in nutrition,

00:06:19.600 --> 00:06:22.780
often increases an uptake on
things like health services

00:06:22.780 --> 00:06:25.690
or actual improvements in health
in terms of fewer accidents

00:06:25.690 --> 00:06:27.230
or better health.

00:06:27.230 --> 00:06:29.440
You see decreases in stress.

00:06:29.440 --> 00:06:32.500
To give you a sense of
the variety of responses

00:06:32.500 --> 00:06:35.440
to cash or to security,
one study in Malawi

00:06:35.440 --> 00:06:38.470
tested giving the
families of young women

00:06:38.470 --> 00:06:41.470
a small recurring cash
payments-- so just a little bit

00:06:41.470 --> 00:06:43.900
of security, not a
total game changer.

00:06:43.900 --> 00:06:47.500
What they found is that those
women whose families received

00:06:47.500 --> 00:06:49.790
got married later,
pregnant later,

00:06:49.790 --> 00:06:52.810
and had lower rates of HIV
relative to the control group.

00:06:52.810 --> 00:06:56.350
Because they had a little
bit more security in society.

00:06:56.350 --> 00:06:58.790
On the other side
of the spectrum,

00:06:58.790 --> 00:07:03.750
a study testing giving young
people about $400 all at once,

00:07:03.750 --> 00:07:06.610
if they went back and
compared that group of people

00:07:06.610 --> 00:07:08.740
to a control group, and
found that their earnings

00:07:08.740 --> 00:07:10.450
were 40% higher.

00:07:10.450 --> 00:07:13.360
That basic result was mirrored
in GiveDirectly study that

00:07:13.360 --> 00:07:16.450
found that a year after
people received about $1,000,

00:07:16.450 --> 00:07:18.910
their earnings were 30%
higher and their assets

00:07:18.910 --> 00:07:21.970
were 58% higher.

00:07:21.970 --> 00:07:24.190
The other things you
don't see are the things

00:07:24.190 --> 00:07:25.657
people are often worried about.

00:07:25.657 --> 00:07:27.740
There is this sense that
if you give people money,

00:07:27.740 --> 00:07:28.690
they might drink it.

00:07:28.690 --> 00:07:31.690
Or it will be corrupting,
and they'll stop working.

00:07:31.690 --> 00:07:33.820
But all of the evidence
we have from what's

00:07:33.820 --> 00:07:38.170
been 165 different studies of
cash transfers, which suggest

00:07:38.170 --> 00:07:39.760
that that doesn't happen.

00:07:39.760 --> 00:07:43.840
The studies have found that
this consumption of, quote,

00:07:43.840 --> 00:07:46.390
"temptation goods"-- things
like alcohol or tobacco

00:07:46.390 --> 00:07:49.480
or gambling-- either has stayed
the same for cash recipients

00:07:49.480 --> 00:07:50.780
or has gone down.

00:07:50.780 --> 00:07:53.230
And similarly, the work effort--
how much time people are

00:07:53.230 --> 00:07:54.520
spending working--

00:07:54.520 --> 00:07:56.346
has either stayed
the same or gone up

00:07:56.346 --> 00:07:57.970
in the different
studies that have been

00:07:57.970 --> 00:08:01.760
done in the developing world.

00:08:01.760 --> 00:08:05.440
The other thing that's
happened more recently

00:08:05.440 --> 00:08:07.380
over the last decade
is an explosion

00:08:07.380 --> 00:08:09.130
in mobile money, which
has made delivering

00:08:09.130 --> 00:08:11.160
cash transfers a lot easier.

00:08:11.160 --> 00:08:13.700
And so today, there are 93
countries with mobile money

00:08:13.700 --> 00:08:16.630
and over 400 million
current mobile money users.

00:08:16.630 --> 00:08:19.960
That makes this job of getting
cash into people's hands pretty

00:08:19.960 --> 00:08:21.290
easy.

00:08:21.290 --> 00:08:22.960
And the mobile
money infrastructure

00:08:22.960 --> 00:08:25.660
doesn't have to
be as robust as it

00:08:25.660 --> 00:08:28.000
is in Kenya, which has the
best network in the world.

00:08:28.000 --> 00:08:31.330
It can actually be
pretty lightweight.

00:08:31.330 --> 00:08:34.330
A study we did in
Uganda tested the limits

00:08:34.330 --> 00:08:36.940
to say, how good does the
payments infrastructure have

00:08:36.940 --> 00:08:38.860
to be for mobile
payments to work?

00:08:38.860 --> 00:08:41.620
And so we found just about
the most remote place

00:08:41.620 --> 00:08:42.820
you could go to in Uganda--

00:08:42.820 --> 00:08:45.370
a place very, very
North in the country,

00:08:45.370 --> 00:08:47.080
just on the border
with South Sudan--

00:08:47.080 --> 00:08:48.910
where people typically
would walk something

00:08:48.910 --> 00:08:51.670
like four or five hours to
get to the nearest town,

00:08:51.670 --> 00:08:54.470
which was also where the
nearest paved road would be.

00:08:54.470 --> 00:08:57.100
We found that if you sent mobile
money to a place that actually

00:08:57.100 --> 00:08:59.980
didn't have any mobile money
providers there already,

00:08:59.980 --> 00:09:04.660
this market responded-- that the
market incentives for cashing

00:09:04.660 --> 00:09:05.920
people out worked.

00:09:05.920 --> 00:09:09.340
And agents came to the
village to cash people out.

00:09:09.340 --> 00:09:13.210
And so this technology exists
to get cash into people's hands

00:09:13.210 --> 00:09:16.200
really, really cheaply.

00:09:16.200 --> 00:09:18.450
As a result of those,
there are two trends.

00:09:18.450 --> 00:09:20.220
There's a ton of
different applications

00:09:20.220 --> 00:09:23.190
where we can use cash
transfers to solve or address

00:09:23.190 --> 00:09:25.325
a bunch of different
types of problems.

00:09:25.325 --> 00:09:26.700
And so to give
you a sense, these

00:09:26.700 --> 00:09:29.700
are some of the projects
GiveDirectly is working on

00:09:29.700 --> 00:09:31.210
around the world.

00:09:31.210 --> 00:09:33.590
And so the first one is the
thing we've done most often.

00:09:33.590 --> 00:09:37.085
It's these large one time
cash grants of about $1,000.

00:09:37.085 --> 00:09:38.460
And I think these
are best geared

00:09:38.460 --> 00:09:41.850
if you want to give
people investment capital.

00:09:41.850 --> 00:09:43.770
And so you see bigger
increases in earnings

00:09:43.770 --> 00:09:48.310
that expect large increases in
assets and things like that.

00:09:48.310 --> 00:09:51.200
You can also use cash transfers
to address humanitarian issues.

00:09:51.200 --> 00:09:53.494
And so we just started
a project in Uganda,

00:09:53.494 --> 00:09:55.410
which has taken in a lot
of different refugees

00:09:55.410 --> 00:09:57.120
from surrounding countries.

00:09:57.120 --> 00:09:59.670
The typical approach to
these types of crises

00:09:59.670 --> 00:10:03.690
is to pay people who run
settlement camps per head

00:10:03.690 --> 00:10:06.090
by this number of people
they're supporting.

00:10:06.090 --> 00:10:08.550
And while that seems intuitive,
the incentives are all off.

00:10:08.550 --> 00:10:10.770
Because the incentives
are to keep people alive,

00:10:10.770 --> 00:10:13.810
but not support them to
move on with their lives.

00:10:13.810 --> 00:10:15.720
And so the test
we're doing in Uganda

00:10:15.720 --> 00:10:19.110
now is giving people about
$750 and letting them

00:10:19.110 --> 00:10:21.360
to spend it however they want.

00:10:21.360 --> 00:10:25.231
You can also use cash for things
like a universal basic income.

00:10:25.231 --> 00:10:27.480
And so I'm sure we'll talk
about this more in Q and A.

00:10:27.480 --> 00:10:30.090
But the basic idea here is
if you want to make sure

00:10:30.090 --> 00:10:33.120
that everybody is living up to
a certain standard of living,

00:10:33.120 --> 00:10:35.220
one way to kind of
mechanically insure

00:10:35.220 --> 00:10:38.370
that is to give everyone a
cash transfer equal to the cost

00:10:38.370 --> 00:10:40.000
of that standard of living.

00:10:40.000 --> 00:10:41.500
And so GiveDirectly
just launched

00:10:41.500 --> 00:10:44.580
to study in Kenya distributing
different types of cash

00:10:44.580 --> 00:10:47.040
transfers to about
16,000 people,

00:10:47.040 --> 00:10:49.380
with some people receiving
a universal basic income

00:10:49.380 --> 00:10:51.570
for up to 12 years.

00:10:51.570 --> 00:10:53.910
On the other side
of the spectrum,

00:10:53.910 --> 00:10:56.766
you can use cash transfers for
things like disaster relief.

00:10:56.766 --> 00:10:58.140
And so something
GiveDirectly did

00:10:58.140 --> 00:11:00.780
this year is launch in
Texas and Puerto Rico

00:11:00.780 --> 00:11:03.995
and hand people out debit
cards for about $1,500.

00:11:03.995 --> 00:11:05.370
That's not a life
changing amount

00:11:05.370 --> 00:11:07.240
of money in either
of those places.

00:11:07.240 --> 00:11:08.940
But it does help
sort of fill the gaps

00:11:08.940 --> 00:11:12.240
in terms of what people aren't
receiving from the existing

00:11:12.240 --> 00:11:15.490
support network or the existing
NGOs doing disaster relief.

00:11:15.490 --> 00:11:18.120
And it lets people buy
whatever is their top priority

00:11:18.120 --> 00:11:20.470
within that price range.

00:11:20.470 --> 00:11:22.320
There's a big
industry that exists

00:11:22.320 --> 00:11:25.560
around things like fair
trade or CSR for companies

00:11:25.560 --> 00:11:28.210
to try to give back to the
people they are working with.

00:11:28.210 --> 00:11:30.940
And so one thing we're testing
with a sort of foundation

00:11:30.940 --> 00:11:34.050
arm of a coffee company is
just giving cash transfers

00:11:34.050 --> 00:11:36.130
in a coffee growing area.

00:11:36.130 --> 00:11:39.060
And so we're working
in eastern Uganda.

00:11:39.060 --> 00:11:41.650
Picked an area which is
growing a lot of coffee and

00:11:41.650 --> 00:11:45.090
are giving people about
the same $1,000 cash grants

00:11:45.090 --> 00:11:47.737
and seeing how it in
general changes their lives,

00:11:47.737 --> 00:11:49.320
as well as how it
changes their coffee

00:11:49.320 --> 00:11:52.560
growing practices, whether
they start doing longer term

00:11:52.560 --> 00:11:54.360
practices and how they
approach the plants

00:11:54.360 --> 00:11:55.756
and things like that.

00:11:55.756 --> 00:11:58.380
And this last thing is a project
that I'm really excited about,

00:11:58.380 --> 00:12:00.600
which is something we're
doing with USAID in Rwanda

00:12:00.600 --> 00:12:03.600
and potentially other
countries, which is using cash

00:12:03.600 --> 00:12:06.559
as a literal benchmark for
their existing programming.

00:12:06.559 --> 00:12:08.850
And so we're running side by
side randomized controlled

00:12:08.850 --> 00:12:13.780
trials in Rwanda, testing
for goals that they have.

00:12:13.780 --> 00:12:16.500
And so in one case,
it's a nutrition program

00:12:16.500 --> 00:12:19.440
that has specific nutrition
goals how we could structure

00:12:19.440 --> 00:12:22.920
a cash transfer program
designed to meet those goals

00:12:22.920 --> 00:12:26.430
and basically produce a report
card answering the question.

00:12:26.430 --> 00:12:28.244
Is the programming
you're doing better

00:12:28.244 --> 00:12:30.660
than just giving the people
you're trying to help the cash

00:12:30.660 --> 00:12:32.040
and letting them spend it?

00:12:32.040 --> 00:12:35.490
And so that provides a literal
benchmark for us to say,

00:12:35.490 --> 00:12:37.260
are we allocating
money correctly?

00:12:40.417 --> 00:12:42.670
And so something that's been
happening in this sector

00:12:42.670 --> 00:12:45.770
as we've had this mountain
of evidence build up

00:12:45.770 --> 00:12:48.010
and as the logistics
of delivering cash

00:12:48.010 --> 00:12:50.650
has become a lot easier
is that the rhetoric

00:12:50.650 --> 00:12:52.180
has changed dramatically.

00:12:52.180 --> 00:12:55.120
It's less so that the
idea of giving cash

00:12:55.120 --> 00:12:58.319
is seen as crazy or
nuts or corrupting.

00:12:58.319 --> 00:13:00.610
And instead, you see things
like this from Ban-Ki Moon.

00:13:00.610 --> 00:13:02.110
He said that cash
programming should

00:13:02.110 --> 00:13:04.990
be the preferred and
default method of support.

00:13:04.990 --> 00:13:07.610
A different sort of summary
of the evidence on cash

00:13:07.610 --> 00:13:09.610
called it perhaps the
most thoroughly researched

00:13:09.610 --> 00:13:11.410
intervention out there.

00:13:11.410 --> 00:13:14.110
And so that's actually
extremely exciting,

00:13:14.110 --> 00:13:16.420
except that the
funding hasn't changed.

00:13:16.420 --> 00:13:19.690
If you look at the overall
portfolio of how we're

00:13:19.690 --> 00:13:21.620
spending our money
to help people,

00:13:21.620 --> 00:13:23.980
it's still spent mostly
not by the recipients

00:13:23.980 --> 00:13:26.290
we're trying to help, and
instead by policymakers

00:13:26.290 --> 00:13:29.440
and bureaucrats and donors
in places like New York

00:13:29.440 --> 00:13:30.910
or D.C. or London.

00:13:30.910 --> 00:13:34.090
And so less than 1% of US
aid funding is cash-based.

00:13:34.090 --> 00:13:37.420
Less than 2% funding of UK
aid funding is cash-based.

00:13:37.420 --> 00:13:40.840
And the same is true in the
humanitarian sectors as well.

00:13:40.840 --> 00:13:43.180
And I'll pause to note
that the rest of the pie

00:13:43.180 --> 00:13:45.290
is not the give
well top charities.

00:13:45.290 --> 00:13:48.460
That's not the kind of most
evidence type interventions

00:13:48.460 --> 00:13:49.210
out there.

00:13:49.210 --> 00:13:51.545
There's a remarkable
inertia in the sector

00:13:51.545 --> 00:13:52.920
that we're still
trying to fight.

00:13:55.830 --> 00:13:58.650
And the consequence is
that because we're not

00:13:58.650 --> 00:14:01.470
solving the allocation
problem at the front,

00:14:01.470 --> 00:14:03.030
it gets solved on
the back end a lot.

00:14:03.030 --> 00:14:05.280
And so you see things like
this from one refugee camp

00:14:05.280 --> 00:14:08.396
where 70% of Syrian refugees
were selling portions

00:14:08.396 --> 00:14:10.770
of food aid they were receiving
to get what they actually

00:14:10.770 --> 00:14:11.680
wanted.

00:14:11.680 --> 00:14:13.380
And so the markets
are still responding

00:14:13.380 --> 00:14:16.740
to try to correct the allocation
but only further and further

00:14:16.740 --> 00:14:20.730
down the chain after we've
shipped food from other places

00:14:20.730 --> 00:14:22.879
into the country.

00:14:22.879 --> 00:14:24.170
And so what can we do about it?

00:14:24.170 --> 00:14:27.190
We have these really
effective tools.

00:14:27.190 --> 00:14:28.180
We have this evidence.

00:14:28.180 --> 00:14:31.810
As donors, how can we
approach this basic problem?

00:14:31.810 --> 00:14:34.360
Well, part of this
stagnation in the sector

00:14:34.360 --> 00:14:37.480
is that it doesn't
respond how like consumer

00:14:37.480 --> 00:14:39.970
goods or, in general, a
market economy respond.

00:14:39.970 --> 00:14:42.130
And so if you look at
a phone like a product,

00:14:42.130 --> 00:14:44.740
we've had remarkable innovation.

00:14:44.740 --> 00:14:49.210
We've gone from this rotary dial
landline phones to the iPhone X

00:14:49.210 --> 00:14:50.242
or something like that.

00:14:50.242 --> 00:14:52.450
And the reason is because
there are market incentives

00:14:52.450 --> 00:14:54.896
to respond to the consumer.

00:14:54.896 --> 00:14:56.770
Well, the problem with
the development sector

00:14:56.770 --> 00:14:59.050
is that the donor is
the person who pays.

00:14:59.050 --> 00:15:01.330
But the recipient is the
person who is affected.

00:15:01.330 --> 00:15:03.580
And so you don't see the
same types of incentives

00:15:03.580 --> 00:15:06.240
exist to have the same
type of innovation.

00:15:06.240 --> 00:15:09.910
And so you often see persistence
in the same types of tools

00:15:09.910 --> 00:15:12.260
that we use again and again.

00:15:12.260 --> 00:15:15.330
And so somehow we have
to become better donors.

00:15:15.330 --> 00:15:18.539
And so these are three questions
you can use to force that

00:15:18.539 --> 00:15:20.080
and to force the
organizations you're

00:15:20.080 --> 00:15:24.040
working with to be more and more
responsive to the people you

00:15:24.040 --> 00:15:26.009
and they are trying to help.

00:15:26.009 --> 00:15:27.550
The first one is
trying to understand

00:15:27.550 --> 00:15:30.850
what the end-to-end cost
of the intervention is.

00:15:30.850 --> 00:15:33.850
How much of your donation
actually ends up in value

00:15:33.850 --> 00:15:36.310
provided to the recipient
at the end of the road?

00:15:36.310 --> 00:15:38.690
Now, there's lots of problems
with overhead metrics

00:15:38.690 --> 00:15:39.770
and things like that.

00:15:39.770 --> 00:15:41.087
And this is not that.

00:15:41.087 --> 00:15:42.670
A problem with the
sector is that it's

00:15:42.670 --> 00:15:44.230
heavily intermediated.

00:15:44.230 --> 00:15:46.360
And so one nonprofit
will take your donation

00:15:46.360 --> 00:15:48.970
and give it to another
nonprofit after sort of skimming

00:15:48.970 --> 00:15:50.037
a little bit off the top.

00:15:50.037 --> 00:15:52.120
They'll skim a little bit
off the top for overhead

00:15:52.120 --> 00:15:53.920
and give it to
another nonprofit.

00:15:53.920 --> 00:15:56.650
And even if the reported
overhead is very low,

00:15:56.650 --> 00:15:59.532
each of those nonprofits
only taking about 1%,

00:15:59.532 --> 00:16:02.740
the systemic overhead
is extraordinarily high.

00:16:02.740 --> 00:16:05.080
If you have a chain of
those nonprofits repeatedly

00:16:05.080 --> 00:16:07.330
subgranting to each
other, the end value

00:16:07.330 --> 00:16:09.930
that's reaching the recipient
is actually very, very low.

00:16:09.930 --> 00:16:12.430
And that's a practice that you
see again and again and again

00:16:12.430 --> 00:16:14.110
in the sector.

00:16:14.110 --> 00:16:17.860
The next thing is
evidence backing.

00:16:17.860 --> 00:16:20.920
Has there been an external
randomized controlled trial

00:16:20.920 --> 00:16:23.950
of this sort of intervention the
organization is implementing?

00:16:23.950 --> 00:16:25.822
How do we actually
know that it works?

00:16:25.822 --> 00:16:27.280
And use the same
standard you would

00:16:27.280 --> 00:16:29.320
want for a medicine
you would take

00:16:29.320 --> 00:16:32.240
or a product that you
would bet your life on.

00:16:32.240 --> 00:16:34.810
And lastly, there's
this benchmark question.

00:16:34.810 --> 00:16:37.600
Is the funding you're
providing to the organization

00:16:37.600 --> 00:16:39.400
and the program that
they're implementing

00:16:39.400 --> 00:16:42.280
doing more good than the people
you're actually trying to help

00:16:42.280 --> 00:16:44.134
could if you just
gave them the cash?

00:16:44.134 --> 00:16:46.300
Now, there's plenty of
interventions that might meet

00:16:46.300 --> 00:16:49.150
that standard-- very specialized
medical interventions,

00:16:49.150 --> 00:16:53.450
for example, or cases where
there's a public good problem--

00:16:53.450 --> 00:16:55.400
infrastructure, or
maybe rule of law.

00:16:55.400 --> 00:16:57.712
There's a particularly good
giving opportunity there.

00:16:57.712 --> 00:16:59.170
But a lot of the
things we're doing

00:16:59.170 --> 00:17:02.140
are trying to outspend
the poor about things

00:17:02.140 --> 00:17:03.790
that they know far more about.

00:17:03.790 --> 00:17:06.640
And so I think a lot of
the spending we're doing

00:17:06.640 --> 00:17:10.732
wouldn't meet this
sort of basic test.

00:17:10.732 --> 00:17:12.190
I think the last
thing that's worth

00:17:12.190 --> 00:17:13.849
pausing on before
we go to Q and A

00:17:13.849 --> 00:17:15.640
and dig into a bunch
of other things

00:17:15.640 --> 00:17:18.130
is why is it worth
giving at all.

00:17:18.130 --> 00:17:20.859
And here I would
say the existence

00:17:20.859 --> 00:17:23.630
of incredible opportunities
to have impact.

00:17:23.630 --> 00:17:24.859
I think cash is one of those.

00:17:24.859 --> 00:17:26.400
But there's lots of
other non-profits

00:17:26.400 --> 00:17:27.819
that are actually
doing good work.

00:17:27.819 --> 00:17:30.820
Provides a pretty
amazing opportunity

00:17:30.820 --> 00:17:33.280
to do something
great with your life

00:17:33.280 --> 00:17:36.460
that almost as a side product
of your day-to-day life

00:17:36.460 --> 00:17:39.040
by donating a certain
small percent.

00:17:39.040 --> 00:17:42.160
Your life can be basically the
same, except as a side product,

00:17:42.160 --> 00:17:45.370
you can dramatically change
and better lives of people who

00:17:45.370 --> 00:17:46.880
are living in extreme poverty.

00:17:46.880 --> 00:17:52.030
And that's a cool opportunity to
do with your 80 years on earth.

00:17:52.030 --> 00:17:57.700
And so I think despite the
dark look on the sector,

00:17:57.700 --> 00:18:01.210
I think there is this incredible
opportunity out there provided

00:18:01.210 --> 00:18:05.530
by good giving opportunities
that make giving worth doing.

00:18:05.530 --> 00:18:07.630
And so with that, I'll
turn it over to questions

00:18:07.630 --> 00:18:09.130
and looking forward
to conversation.

00:18:09.130 --> 00:18:10.870
