00:19:59.480 --> 00:20:03.230
like Google does to
change currencies?

00:20:03.230 --> 00:20:05.720
It seems like something that's
really important to the flow

00:20:05.720 --> 00:20:08.450
of money in this organization.

00:20:08.450 --> 00:20:11.390
And I wonder if
there's an opportunity

00:20:11.390 --> 00:20:14.870
for multinational
corporations to help out

00:20:14.870 --> 00:20:17.430
not just by matching
employees donations,

00:20:17.430 --> 00:20:22.010
but maybe to assist
with currency exchange

00:20:22.010 --> 00:20:23.930
in the currencies
that they're already

00:20:23.930 --> 00:20:27.050
exchanging in gigantic
quantities on a very

00:20:27.050 --> 00:20:29.330
frequent basis.

00:20:29.330 --> 00:20:31.730
JOE HUSTON: Yeah,
it's interesting.

00:20:31.730 --> 00:20:36.860
The history of what we
have paid has changed.

00:20:36.860 --> 00:20:38.805
I think when we were
first getting started,

00:20:38.805 --> 00:20:39.680
we were pretty naive.

00:20:39.680 --> 00:20:43.820
And so we were paying about
a percent per transaction,

00:20:43.820 --> 00:20:46.370
which would be extremely high
for developed world currencies.

00:20:46.370 --> 00:20:49.610
It's a little bit what you'd
expect for the developing world

00:20:49.610 --> 00:20:51.729
currencies we're trading in.

00:20:51.729 --> 00:20:53.270
I think we've gotten
better over time

00:20:53.270 --> 00:20:55.710
at competing different
banks against each other.

00:20:55.710 --> 00:20:58.160
And so we have a US
bank that quotes a rate.

00:20:58.160 --> 00:21:00.650
But we also competed against
certain different local banks.

00:21:00.650 --> 00:21:02.608
And we've added different
local banks over time

00:21:02.608 --> 00:21:05.340
to impart offer
competition there,

00:21:05.340 --> 00:21:09.710
but also to offer credit risk
hedges basically while we're

00:21:09.710 --> 00:21:11.030
holding the cash there.

00:21:11.030 --> 00:21:13.670
And so the total
fees we're paying

00:21:13.670 --> 00:21:16.236
have dropped a ton over time.

00:21:16.236 --> 00:21:20.030
And so now we're only
like a hair above 0%

00:21:20.030 --> 00:21:21.350
or something like that.

00:21:21.350 --> 00:21:24.440
That said, my guess is
the Googles or something

00:21:24.440 --> 00:21:26.562
like that are probably
being a step more clever.

00:21:26.562 --> 00:21:28.520
And so my guess is the
same opportunities still

00:21:28.520 --> 00:21:29.195
probably exist.

00:21:32.720 --> 00:21:35.120
I don't know how the tool
would work, the piggybacking

00:21:35.120 --> 00:21:36.020
off the transfers.

00:21:36.020 --> 00:21:40.110
But I bet there is something
there in terms of, yeah,

00:21:40.110 --> 00:21:42.004
trying to be more clever.

00:21:42.004 --> 00:21:44.420
I think also as we've grown,
we've become a bigger player.

00:21:44.420 --> 00:21:46.787
And in these markets,
it's certainly the day

00:21:46.787 --> 00:21:48.120
we trade or something like that.

00:21:48.120 --> 00:21:49.760
And so I think
that's helped in us

00:21:49.760 --> 00:21:54.136
getting better rates versus us
getting first getting started.

00:21:54.136 --> 00:21:54.969
