00:23:11.555 --> 00:23:12.930
including the
directives that are

00:23:12.930 --> 00:23:14.730
sort of testing
the Utopic version

00:23:14.730 --> 00:23:18.480
or the template version,
aren't providing a lot of light

00:23:18.480 --> 00:23:21.390
on how to get there
or on the pilots that

00:23:21.390 --> 00:23:24.150
should happen in the
near-term on policies

00:23:24.150 --> 00:23:26.820
that are more likely in the US.

00:23:26.820 --> 00:23:28.500
I think for a lot
of countries, a UBI

00:23:28.500 --> 00:23:30.240
could feel closer politically--

00:23:30.240 --> 00:23:32.580
India might be one example--

00:23:32.580 --> 00:23:35.940
for which the conversation
and the pilots focusing

00:23:35.940 --> 00:23:38.920
on that template are
actually pretty useful.

00:23:38.920 --> 00:23:41.640
But in the US, I worry a lot
about the distraction factor--

00:23:41.640 --> 00:23:45.360
that we've cut away
the wonk class who

00:23:45.360 --> 00:23:47.340
care about poverty in
the US and focus them

00:23:47.340 --> 00:23:50.294
on a policy that feels far.

00:23:50.294 --> 00:23:50.960
SPEAKER 1: Yeah.

00:23:50.960 --> 00:23:53.180
And EITC is their earned
income tax credit.

00:23:53.180 --> 00:23:56.240
It's a very large cash
transfer in the US.

00:23:56.240 --> 00:23:58.530
Also note in the comments
of this question,

00:23:58.530 --> 00:24:00.990
there was a lot of
discussion on inflation.

00:24:00.990 --> 00:24:03.140
So there was a study
that was recently

00:24:03.140 --> 00:24:06.087
pursued from the Mexican
cash transfer program.

00:24:06.087 --> 00:24:07.920
I don't know if you
want to talk about that.

00:24:07.920 --> 00:24:10.865
But it seemed to find that
there was not inflation.

00:24:10.865 --> 00:24:11.555
JOE HUSTON: Yes.

00:24:11.555 --> 00:24:12.930
SPEAKER 1: Or if
you're familiar.

00:24:12.930 --> 00:24:13.888
JOE HUSTON: Yeah, yeah.

00:24:13.888 --> 00:24:18.241
And so Mexico was in that chart
of the different cash transfer

00:24:18.241 --> 00:24:18.740
programs.

00:24:18.740 --> 00:24:21.020
They were one of the
leading innovators

00:24:21.020 --> 00:24:22.820
both in implementing
a cash transfer

00:24:22.820 --> 00:24:25.710
program in the developing world
and in actually testing it.

00:24:25.710 --> 00:24:28.460
And so the US had different
types of cash support

00:24:28.460 --> 00:24:29.060
before then.

00:24:29.060 --> 00:24:31.910
But they were really forward
thinking as a government

00:24:31.910 --> 00:24:33.920
and working with
academics to test

00:24:33.920 --> 00:24:36.204
the effects of cash transfers.

00:24:36.204 --> 00:24:38.120
And so they produced
some of the early results

00:24:38.120 --> 00:24:41.450
on just how cash transfers
work on the individual level.

00:24:41.450 --> 00:24:43.640
But then also a recent
analysis of those programs

00:24:43.640 --> 00:24:46.820
found that you don't see
the kind of doomsday things

00:24:46.820 --> 00:24:49.460
people are worried about
in terms of a basic income

00:24:49.460 --> 00:24:51.890
or in general expanding cash
transfer programs in terms

00:24:51.890 --> 00:24:55.880
of prices just going up
a ton to totally offset

00:24:55.880 --> 00:24:57.500
the value of the cash.

00:24:57.500 --> 00:25:00.050
That's something that we've seen
in a couple of other studies

00:25:00.050 --> 00:25:02.120
done evaluating that question.

00:25:02.120 --> 00:25:03.950
GiveDirectly's
first study looked

00:25:03.950 --> 00:25:06.200
at a kind of village level
and didn't see any effect

00:25:06.200 --> 00:25:07.400
on prices.

00:25:07.400 --> 00:25:09.980
A thing we have in works
that we don't have results

00:25:09.980 --> 00:25:14.880
out is a study specifically
designed to stress test that.

00:25:14.880 --> 00:25:17.060
And so we used our
one time grants

00:25:17.060 --> 00:25:21.200
and randomized the concentration
of GiveDirectly's enrollment

00:25:21.200 --> 00:25:22.490
within a large region.

00:25:22.490 --> 00:25:24.800
And so there were high
concentration areas

00:25:24.800 --> 00:25:26.750
and very low
concentration areas.

00:25:26.750 --> 00:25:29.840
And then as we delivered what
was massive amounts of cash

00:25:29.840 --> 00:25:32.060
in the region,
researchers looked

00:25:32.060 --> 00:25:34.820
at prices in local
markets as well as

00:25:34.820 --> 00:25:39.070
quantity of goods supplied,
local taxes, and school fee

00:25:39.070 --> 00:25:41.435
payments, these sorts of
different kind of macro

00:25:41.435 --> 00:25:43.020
or community level effects.

00:25:43.020 --> 00:25:46.350
And so those are results I think
we'll have out early next year

00:25:46.350 --> 00:25:50.450
or so that I hope can contribute
to that debate as well.

00:25:50.450 --> 00:25:53.810
I think on the theory of
it, a lot of the ways people

00:25:53.810 --> 00:25:58.339
talk about inflation, the
Econ model is too simple.

00:25:58.339 --> 00:25:59.880
That they're sort
of holding constant

00:25:59.880 --> 00:26:01.550
how much can be supplied.

00:26:01.550 --> 00:26:04.020
That a lot of times
either big companies

00:26:04.020 --> 00:26:06.390
can respond to
increases in demand

00:26:06.390 --> 00:26:07.807
by supplying more of the good.

00:26:07.807 --> 00:26:10.140
Or oftentimes in the developing
world, something you see

00:26:10.140 --> 00:26:15.260
is the cash given
increases the supply.

00:26:15.260 --> 00:26:19.410
And so an example could
be you would be worried

00:26:19.410 --> 00:26:21.840
that you gave cash to an area.

00:26:21.840 --> 00:26:24.190
And the area in general
likes consuming fish.

00:26:24.190 --> 00:26:26.076
And so the price
of fish will go up.

00:26:26.076 --> 00:26:27.450
But the piece that
you're missing

00:26:27.450 --> 00:26:29.241
is that often when
people receive the cash,

00:26:29.241 --> 00:26:33.450
they buy boats or fishing nets
or coolers to be middlemen

00:26:33.450 --> 00:26:35.190
between fishermen and markets.

00:26:35.190 --> 00:26:37.950
And so actually this
quantity of supply of fish

00:26:37.950 --> 00:26:39.970
goes up as much or more.

00:26:39.970 --> 00:26:43.380
And so I think the model
people use to answer and think

00:26:43.380 --> 00:26:46.590
about the inflation question
has to not keep supply

00:26:46.590 --> 00:26:48.310
fixed when debating that part.

00:26:54.814 --> 00:26:55.480
AUDIENCE: Hello?

00:26:58.710 --> 00:27:00.590
Can I ask a question?

00:27:00.590 --> 00:27:01.340
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:27:01.340 --> 00:27:03.230
OK, sorry.

00:27:03.230 --> 00:27:05.930
I would like to learn a little
bit more about your UBI pilot

00:27:05.930 --> 00:27:07.400
in Kenya, you said.

00:27:07.400 --> 00:27:09.830
And I know we have already
talked about UBI a little bit,

00:27:09.830 --> 00:27:13.370
but I guess there's a reason
behind GiveDirectly jumping

00:27:13.370 --> 00:27:16.130
into basic income and
you providing the service

00:27:16.130 --> 00:27:18.320
to 12,000 people, I think.

00:27:18.320 --> 00:27:20.690
And I'm always
wondering how can you

00:27:20.690 --> 00:27:23.510
get from those results you're
getting from the UBI, which

00:27:23.510 --> 00:27:26.180
is only paid to a fraction
of people in the country,

00:27:26.180 --> 00:27:29.250
then to a more universal aspect
where all people would receive

00:27:29.250 --> 00:27:29.750
it?

00:27:29.750 --> 00:27:31.490
And what are you
hoping to learn?

00:27:31.490 --> 00:27:33.920
And do you have any
results as of far?

00:27:33.920 --> 00:27:34.910
JOE HUSTON: Yes.

00:27:34.910 --> 00:27:39.080
And so when GiveDirectly was
seeing the debate on UBI spike

00:27:39.080 --> 00:27:43.790
up again over the last couple of
years, the thing we saw it was

00:27:43.790 --> 00:27:46.040
was a debate about how a
particular type of cash

00:27:46.040 --> 00:27:47.270
transfer works.

00:27:47.270 --> 00:27:49.460
There is these questions
on the pro side

00:27:49.460 --> 00:27:52.160
that it would enable
different types of risk taking

00:27:52.160 --> 00:27:55.821
or entrepreneurship, help
people live their lives better.

00:27:55.821 --> 00:27:57.320
On the con side,
people were worried

00:27:57.320 --> 00:27:59.630
that people would stop
working or spend it badly

00:27:59.630 --> 00:28:01.650
or things like that.

00:28:01.650 --> 00:28:03.920
And those questions
are testable.

00:28:03.920 --> 00:28:06.470
And so like other
people's launching pilots,

00:28:06.470 --> 00:28:08.570
we saw this was very much
within our sweet spot

00:28:08.570 --> 00:28:10.910
to implement a cash
transfer program

00:28:10.910 --> 00:28:14.330
and then work with researchers
to test the results.

00:28:14.330 --> 00:28:17.120
The basic structure
we used was to design

00:28:17.120 --> 00:28:20.690
to test what's unique about a
UBI versus other cash transfer

00:28:20.690 --> 00:28:21.650
programs.

00:28:21.650 --> 00:28:23.720
And so in part to get at your--

00:28:23.720 --> 00:28:26.460
a big piece of a UBI
is that it's universal.

00:28:26.460 --> 00:28:28.850
And so we randomized
at the village level

00:28:28.850 --> 00:28:31.790
with whole villages randomly
assigned to receive cash

00:28:31.790 --> 00:28:33.164
or not.

00:28:33.164 --> 00:28:34.580
And then we also
randomly assigned

00:28:34.580 --> 00:28:37.820
some villages to receive cash
for 12 years and some villages

00:28:37.820 --> 00:28:39.380
to receive cash for two.

00:28:39.380 --> 00:28:41.472
Because a scaled
up version of a UBI

00:28:41.472 --> 00:28:42.680
would be for your whole life.

00:28:42.680 --> 00:28:46.060
But a lot of the pilots
that have been done

00:28:46.060 --> 00:28:48.194
and that are coming
online are shorter term.

00:28:48.194 --> 00:28:49.610
And so potential
research question

00:28:49.610 --> 00:28:51.590
you might have is
can you extrapolate

00:28:51.590 --> 00:28:55.070
to how the incentives would
actually be for people if they

00:28:55.070 --> 00:28:56.870
had that longer term security?

00:28:56.870 --> 00:29:00.270
Again, on the pro
side and the con side.

00:29:00.270 --> 00:29:04.760
And so that full
study just kicked off

00:29:04.760 --> 00:29:05.960
a couple of weeks ago.

00:29:05.960 --> 00:29:08.940
And so it'll be a little bit
aways before we have results.

00:29:08.940 --> 00:29:10.640
The first end lines
and things like

00:29:10.640 --> 00:29:12.400
that will be within
the next year or so.

00:29:12.400 --> 00:29:13.820
So it won't be 12 years.

00:29:13.820 --> 00:29:15.470
But it will be a
little bit of time.

00:29:15.470 --> 00:29:19.340
That said, about a year ago,
we started providing payments

00:29:19.340 --> 00:29:21.230
in one kind of pilot village.

00:29:21.230 --> 00:29:23.840
And so it got to sort
of ask people what it's

00:29:23.840 --> 00:29:25.340
like to receive a basic income.

00:29:25.340 --> 00:29:27.200
And obviously that's
totally anecdotal.

00:29:27.200 --> 00:29:29.260
It shouldn't be confused
with the RCT evidence.

00:29:29.260 --> 00:29:32.310
But even that was
pretty interesting.

00:29:32.310 --> 00:29:35.300
I think if you ask
people what it's

00:29:35.300 --> 00:29:38.401
like, you see the things that
are consistent with the broader

00:29:38.401 --> 00:29:38.900
evidence.

00:29:38.900 --> 00:29:40.650
People spend it in a
ton of different ways

00:29:40.650 --> 00:29:42.440
because they have
different priorities.

00:29:42.440 --> 00:29:46.130
You saw a lot of spending on
food, especially elderly people

00:29:46.130 --> 00:29:47.420
who couldn't work.

00:29:47.420 --> 00:29:50.430
Different types of investments
in people's job or businesses,

00:29:50.430 --> 00:29:54.410
whether that's buying small
amounts of capital for a shoe

00:29:54.410 --> 00:29:55.640
business I saw.

00:29:55.640 --> 00:29:57.350
People actually
buying fishing nets.

00:29:57.350 --> 00:30:00.620
It's an area right on the
edge of Lake Victoria.

00:30:00.620 --> 00:30:02.190
People investing in school fees.

00:30:02.190 --> 00:30:05.180
Secondary school
isn't free in Kenya.

00:30:05.180 --> 00:30:07.680
Health and things like that.

00:30:07.680 --> 00:30:09.140
Some of the unique things were--

00:30:09.140 --> 00:30:12.800
we were worried on the
operational perspective,

00:30:12.800 --> 00:30:16.361
how people would perceive a
UBI, a few different aspects

00:30:16.361 --> 00:30:16.860
of that.

00:30:16.860 --> 00:30:19.400
One of them is universality.

00:30:19.400 --> 00:30:21.389
Even though the village
we're working in

00:30:21.389 --> 00:30:23.180
and the groups of
villages we're working in

00:30:23.180 --> 00:30:25.670
are in absolute terms
all very, very poor,

00:30:25.670 --> 00:30:28.160
there's still a different decent
amount of income variation

00:30:28.160 --> 00:30:29.390
within those villages.

00:30:29.390 --> 00:30:32.660
And so in this particular
one, the poorest people

00:30:32.660 --> 00:30:34.970
had walls you could
essentially see through.

00:30:34.970 --> 00:30:38.150
And the whole house was made
from organic materials-- mud

00:30:38.150 --> 00:30:39.770
and thatch and things like that.

00:30:39.770 --> 00:30:43.450
And the richest
couple had a tractor.

00:30:43.450 --> 00:30:45.980
And so that's a
remarkable distance

00:30:45.980 --> 00:30:48.590
in wealth and in income
and things like that.

00:30:48.590 --> 00:30:51.380
And so one thing we
asked people was just how

00:30:51.380 --> 00:30:53.870
do you feel that everyone's
getting the same amount of cash

00:30:53.870 --> 00:30:54.650
support?

00:30:54.650 --> 00:30:56.030
Does it seem fair?

00:30:56.030 --> 00:30:58.560
Should GiveDirectly,
as we often do,

00:30:58.560 --> 00:31:02.090
try to pick the poorest
people in this village?

00:31:02.090 --> 00:31:04.132
And people responded
pretty uniformly

00:31:04.132 --> 00:31:06.590
that they were like, we were
glad you didn't try to meddle,

00:31:06.590 --> 00:31:09.690
that you didn't try to
pick who should receive.

00:31:09.690 --> 00:31:12.680
And so was pretty interesting
from a perceived fairness

00:31:12.680 --> 00:31:15.170
perspective about
a UBI and connects

00:31:15.170 --> 00:31:17.960
to some of the debate people
have about the stigmatization

00:31:17.960 --> 00:31:21.680
of receiving benefits
or things like that.

00:31:21.680 --> 00:31:24.290
Another, again, qualitative
thing we asked people about

00:31:24.290 --> 00:31:29.480
was whether individually
targeted payments were OK.

00:31:29.480 --> 00:31:31.730
A kind of potential
benefit of a UBI

00:31:31.730 --> 00:31:33.980
is that it frees
people in relationships

00:31:33.980 --> 00:31:36.530
because each person has their
own individual security.

00:31:36.530 --> 00:31:39.020
And so if a
relationship is abusive

00:31:39.020 --> 00:31:41.240
or there's a bad power
dynamic, somebody

00:31:41.240 --> 00:31:44.520
could leave or at least be on
a more level playing field.

00:31:44.520 --> 00:31:46.520
The flip side, if you're
a foreign organization,

00:31:46.520 --> 00:31:47.895
is that it could
look like you're

00:31:47.895 --> 00:31:51.080
trying to break up families by
insisting that each person has

00:31:51.080 --> 00:31:53.530
their own cell phone and
their own stream of payments.

00:31:53.530 --> 00:31:56.780
And so we were worried that
that would be perceived badly.

00:31:56.780 --> 00:31:59.000
Again, the surprise was
that basically everyone

00:31:59.000 --> 00:32:02.300
said just the opposite, that
individually targeted payments

00:32:02.300 --> 00:32:05.840
let people prioritize whatever
was their top priority

00:32:05.840 --> 00:32:07.950
and made debates easier.

00:32:07.950 --> 00:32:10.665
There was this sense of he has
his money, and I have my money.

00:32:10.665 --> 00:32:12.290
And we get to spend
it on what we want.

00:32:12.290 --> 00:32:14.630
And so there's
not as much of a--

00:32:14.630 --> 00:32:17.480
for the UBI payments, a
shared pool that has to be

00:32:17.480 --> 00:32:18.080
fought over.

00:32:18.080 --> 00:32:20.360
And so that was pretty
interesting as well.

00:32:20.360 --> 00:32:21.594
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:32:21.594 --> 00:32:24.920
SPEAKER 1: And yeah, some of the
negative income tax experiments

00:32:24.920 --> 00:32:27.320
in the 70s seemed
at first to suggest

00:32:27.320 --> 00:32:28.760
that divorce rates went up.

00:32:28.760 --> 00:32:30.960
But subsequent analysis
found that it didn't.

00:32:30.960 --> 00:32:35.960
So it's interesting how this
individually versus family

00:32:35.960 --> 00:32:40.286
orientation isn't everything.

00:32:40.286 --> 00:32:42.160
AUDIENCE: I wanted to
learn a little bit more

00:32:42.160 --> 00:32:44.920
about the evaluation of
the cash transfer program.

00:32:44.920 --> 00:32:47.710
So firstly, I wanted
to know how long you

00:32:47.710 --> 00:32:50.710
track people for after they've
received the cash payment?

00:32:50.710 --> 00:32:53.590
And then in terms of
logistics and scaling

00:32:53.590 --> 00:32:56.560
up, do you think that the
evaluation model you have right

00:32:56.560 --> 00:32:59.980
now could be then used
by, say, a USAID or one

00:32:59.980 --> 00:33:03.712
of the other big
donors for evaluating?

00:33:03.712 --> 00:33:04.420
JOE HUSTON: Yeah.

00:33:04.420 --> 00:33:06.929
So it varies a lot by study.

00:33:06.929 --> 00:33:08.470
And so different
studies are targeted

00:33:08.470 --> 00:33:11.860
towards different questions,
which require a different time

00:33:11.860 --> 00:33:12.760
horizon.

00:33:12.760 --> 00:33:18.820
The basic template structure
is first, external researchers.

00:33:18.820 --> 00:33:22.720
And so academics at places like
MIT or Harvard who are helping

00:33:22.720 --> 00:33:26.689
design the study with us and
external research surveying

00:33:26.689 --> 00:33:27.230
organization.

00:33:27.230 --> 00:33:29.470
And so it's not
GiveDirectly staff

00:33:29.470 --> 00:33:31.660
asking people about their
consumption patterns.

00:33:31.660 --> 00:33:34.240
It's different people from
a different organization

00:33:34.240 --> 00:33:37.570
who don't have a
relationship with us.

00:33:37.570 --> 00:33:40.090
It's important to
pre-register the study.

00:33:40.090 --> 00:33:42.490
Basically say, we're
going to do this study.

00:33:42.490 --> 00:33:44.521
Provide a pre-analysis
plan, which says,

00:33:44.521 --> 00:33:46.270
we're going to answer
these questions that

00:33:46.270 --> 00:33:49.170
help solve for cherry
picking on the studies,

00:33:49.170 --> 00:33:50.890
as in not holding
back studies that

00:33:50.890 --> 00:33:53.830
have bad results or no results,
as well as cherry picking

00:33:53.830 --> 00:33:56.770
on the analysis, not
redoing the analysis again

00:33:56.770 --> 00:34:00.040
and again until you get
the results you want.

00:34:00.040 --> 00:34:02.050
After that, in terms
of the horizon,

00:34:02.050 --> 00:34:03.760
again, that's
varied a lot for us.

00:34:03.760 --> 00:34:09.010
We have one study that is going
to have something like 18 month

00:34:09.010 --> 00:34:11.270
results out some
early next year.

00:34:11.270 --> 00:34:14.440
But it's sort of queued up to
track people for a decade or so

00:34:14.440 --> 00:34:17.360
in terms of the sample
size and things like that.

00:34:17.360 --> 00:34:20.199
Because GiveDirectly
is younger, our ability

00:34:20.199 --> 00:34:24.370
to have a super long horizon
already done is harder.

00:34:24.370 --> 00:34:28.420
In the existing literature,
the longest follow up

00:34:28.420 --> 00:34:31.030
is a paper in Uganda.

00:34:31.030 --> 00:34:35.290
That was that $400 cash
grant I mentioned to use.

00:34:35.290 --> 00:34:37.330
And that's gone out to,
I think, the eight year

00:34:37.330 --> 00:34:40.125
mark and found
persistent results.

00:34:40.125 --> 00:34:42.250
And there's been a study
in Sri Lanka that went out

00:34:42.250 --> 00:34:43.960
to five years and found--

00:34:43.960 --> 00:34:46.270
it was cash transfers to
small business people--

00:34:46.270 --> 00:34:50.560
and found at the five year mark
markedly different earnings

00:34:50.560 --> 00:34:53.679
even persisting to that level.

00:34:53.679 --> 00:34:57.490
On terms of scale,
in part, the program

00:34:57.490 --> 00:35:00.530
we were doing with USAID is a
good example of large funders

00:35:00.530 --> 00:35:01.905
are still able to
run those types

00:35:01.905 --> 00:35:03.670
of randomized controlled trials.

00:35:03.670 --> 00:35:07.150
In many ways, the big con about
RCTs is that they're expensive.

00:35:07.150 --> 00:35:09.500
You have to have giant samples.

00:35:09.500 --> 00:35:11.830
You have to be able to fund
things like research costs

