00:39:22.103 --> 00:39:25.730
And each addition of
a country is targeted

00:39:25.730 --> 00:39:27.032
towards a particular goal--

00:39:27.032 --> 00:39:28.490
a research program
that we think is

00:39:28.490 --> 00:39:32.570
especially valuable or
important for policy impact.

00:39:32.570 --> 00:39:34.460
Against that kind
of baseline, the way

00:39:34.460 --> 00:39:37.580
we evaluate new
projects is I think

00:39:37.580 --> 00:39:40.950
a big potential value
of cash transfers

00:39:40.950 --> 00:39:44.250
is the indirect
effects on the sector.

00:39:44.250 --> 00:39:45.960
And there's a few
different sectors,

00:39:45.960 --> 00:39:47.826
whether it's providing
research that's

00:39:47.826 --> 00:39:50.450
especially useful for developing
world governments in designing

00:39:50.450 --> 00:39:52.880
their own cash
transfer programs,

00:39:52.880 --> 00:39:55.580
providing cash transfer
structures that provide

00:39:55.580 --> 00:40:00.180
benchmarks for aid programs
that exist around the world,

00:40:00.180 --> 00:40:02.990
or in general
pushing on the debate

00:40:02.990 --> 00:40:05.900
about how we should help people.

00:40:05.900 --> 00:40:08.900
The Houston and
Puerto Rico examples,

00:40:08.900 --> 00:40:10.910
we debated a lot internally.

00:40:10.910 --> 00:40:13.010
What we saw was
basically an opportunity

00:40:13.010 --> 00:40:17.190
to connect different
conversations.

00:40:17.190 --> 00:40:19.880
A weird thing that happens
in conversations about giving

00:40:19.880 --> 00:40:21.570
and especially
about cash is they

00:40:21.570 --> 00:40:22.940
can stay pretty disjointed.

00:40:22.940 --> 00:40:25.140
And so the basic
income conversation

00:40:25.140 --> 00:40:28.110
can happen without
referencing any of the papers

00:40:28.110 --> 00:40:30.540
within the developing world
about a lot of what we already

00:40:30.540 --> 00:40:32.050
know about how cash
transfers work.

00:40:32.050 --> 00:40:34.110
And so there can be
remarkable ignorance

00:40:34.110 --> 00:40:37.410
about all of the things that
have already been studied.

00:40:37.410 --> 00:40:38.790
We can sort of
throw up our hands

00:40:38.790 --> 00:40:40.656
in Texas about how
do we help people

00:40:40.656 --> 00:40:42.030
without any of
this sort of sense

00:40:42.030 --> 00:40:43.830
of how helpful
cash transfers can

00:40:43.830 --> 00:40:46.060
be in that type of situation.

00:40:46.060 --> 00:40:50.790
And so we sort of saw it as
an opportunity to one, in part

00:40:50.790 --> 00:40:54.670
provide a set of
pipes to deliver cash

00:40:54.670 --> 00:40:58.420
for donors who probably weren't
going to give to East Africa

00:40:58.420 --> 00:40:59.140
otherwise.

00:40:59.140 --> 00:41:01.306
There were people who
specifically wanted to give it

00:41:01.306 --> 00:41:03.020
to Texas or to Puerto Rico.

00:41:03.020 --> 00:41:07.160
And so we could provide
that utility to enable that.

00:41:07.160 --> 00:41:11.770
And then two, provide
the cash alternative

00:41:11.770 --> 00:41:16.390
in a new conversation that we
hope will sort of carry over

00:41:16.390 --> 00:41:18.749
into the broader
conversation in aid

00:41:18.749 --> 00:41:20.540
and in basic income or
something like that.

00:41:20.540 --> 00:41:25.240
And so the bet here, I think,
is that we can sort of connect

00:41:25.240 --> 00:41:27.790
conversations that
are staying disparate

00:41:27.790 --> 00:41:31.297
and that there isn't
otherwise an allocation

00:41:31.297 --> 00:41:32.880
from East Africa to
Texas-- that there

00:41:32.880 --> 00:41:35.290
are different giving pools.

00:41:35.290 --> 00:41:37.000
And if that's the
case, then it's

00:41:37.000 --> 00:41:38.541
absolutely the case
that there should

00:41:38.541 --> 00:41:41.170
be some type of utility
for people to give to Texas

00:41:41.170 --> 00:41:44.950
and to help those people
better than existing

00:41:44.950 --> 00:41:46.990
opportunities had.

00:41:46.990 --> 00:41:49.532
SPEAKER 1: We'll move
