00:44:17.295 --> 00:44:20.870
but one last question on
the transfer efficiency

00:44:20.870 --> 00:44:24.340
of the basic income experiment
relative to cash transfers

00:44:24.340 --> 00:44:27.702
and maybe long run
expectations there.

00:44:27.702 --> 00:44:28.410
JOE HUSTON: Yeah.

00:44:28.410 --> 00:44:35.030
And so the different trade offs
for the basic income experiment

00:44:35.030 --> 00:44:38.110
are there are more payments.

00:44:38.110 --> 00:44:41.740
And mobile money providers
have a per payment fee.

00:44:41.740 --> 00:44:44.110
And so there is more payments
per value distributed.

00:44:44.110 --> 00:44:46.850
And so mobile money fees
are a little bit higher.

00:44:46.850 --> 00:44:50.050
We have to have our call center
running longer per recipient

00:44:50.050 --> 00:44:51.980
because people are getting
paid for two years.

00:44:51.980 --> 00:44:54.040
And so there's higher
follow up costs.

00:44:54.040 --> 00:44:56.710
That said, the total
value distributed

00:44:56.710 --> 00:45:03.730
is higher per recipient than
our typical $1,000 payments.

00:45:03.730 --> 00:45:06.250
And the way that all nets
is that the two-year arm

00:45:06.250 --> 00:45:07.580
is much less efficient.

00:45:07.580 --> 00:45:10.030
It's something like 75% or 80%.

00:45:10.030 --> 00:45:13.390
The 12-year arm is
much more efficient.

00:45:13.390 --> 00:45:17.200
And the combination of those
two, the weighted average

00:45:17.200 --> 00:45:22.370
across those different arms is
about in that 88%, 90% range.

00:45:22.370 --> 00:45:24.790
The next question on efficiency
was actually [? Harvey, ?]

00:45:24.790 --> 00:45:26.910
which is pretty interesting.

